<H3> <TI>   Thai Minister's Comments on U.S. Military Role Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1801062494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0613 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1801062494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bangkok, January 18 (XINHUA) -- The United States 
will not totally drop its military role in Southeast Asia but 
rather change its form, Thai Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri 
said on Monday [18 January]. 
  The minister was replying to a question as to how he viewed 
the U.S. future role in the region just before the visit of 
former U.S. President George Bush who is scheduled to arrive in 
Bangkok tonight as the guest of business tycoon Charoen Pokphand. 
  Prasong was quoted by the local newspaper "THE BANGKOK POST" 
as saying that there would be no official discussion between 
Bush and himself on regional security, but adding he would brief 
the former President on the situation if asked to do so. 

